│ how they assess the cost of vectorizing this specific        │
│ loop.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe Scalar          │
│ Evolution analysis provides a crucial clue:\n```\n%for = phi │
│ i32 [ 4, %entry ], [ %iv, %loop ]\n-->  %for U: [0,9) S:     │
│ [0,9)  Exits: <<Unknown>>  LoopDispositions: { %loop:        │
│ Variant }\n```\nSCEV correctly identifies `%for` as          │
│ \"Variant\". This is because it's a first-order recurrence:  │
│ its value in the current iteration (`%iv`) depends on the    │
│ induction variable from the *previous* iteration. This is    │
│ different from a standard induction or reduction             │
│ recurrence.\n\nThe core of the issue is how the two cost     │
│ models evaluate the profitability of vectorizing this        │
│ specific type of recurrence. The assertion failure implies   │
│ one model decided to vectorize (VF > 1) while the other      │
│ decided not to (VF = 1).\n\n### 3. Root Cause                │
│ Analysis\n\nThe disagreement stems from how the legacy cost  │
│ model handles first-order recurrences. To vectorize the      │
│ `%for` PHI, the vectorizer must \"scalarize\" the            │
│ dependency. This involves generating code to get the value   │
│ of `%iv` from the last lane of the previous vector iteration │
│ and using it as the first lane for the `%for` vector in the  │
│ current iteration. This is typically done with               │
│ `extractelement` and `insertelement` instructions, which     │
│ have a cost.\n\nThe legacy cost model, specifically in       │
│ `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getRecurrenceCost`, contains    │
│ logic to estimate the cost of this scalarization. A key part │
│ of this logic is a profitability heuristic:\n\n```cpp\n//    │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp\n\n// This   │
│ is a first-order recurrence. This will be implemented by     │
│ vector\n// extracting the last scalar value of the VF-1      │
│ elements and then vector\n// inserting the new value to the  │
│ beginning of the vector.\nif (Phi->hasOneUse()) {\n  // If   │
│ the PHI has only one use, we can't scalarize it.\n  // TODO: │
│ We should be able to scalarize it.\n  return                 │
│ Cost->getImpossibleCost();\n}\n```\nThe code previously had  │
│ a check that would deem this operation too expensive if the  │
│ recurrence PHI node (`%for`) had only one user. In the       │
│ provided reproducer, `%for` is only used by the `sub`        │
│ instruction, so it has exactly one use. Consequently, the    │
│ legacy cost model assigned a very high (effectively          │
│ infinite) cost, forcing `LegacyVF.Width` to be 1 (i.e., do   │
│ not vectorize).\n\nThe newer VPlan-based model, however,     │
│ correctly estimates a finite cost for the necessary          │
│ shuffle/insert/extract operations and determines that        │
│ vectorization is profitable, selecting a `BestFactor.Width`  │
│ greater than 1.\n\nThis discrepancy\u2014legacy model        │
│ refusing to vectorize due to the single-use heuristic, and   │
│ the VPlan model agreeing to\u2014is the direct cause of the  │
│ assertion failure. The heuristic in the legacy model was     │
│ overly pessimistic. The fix is to remove this overly         │
│ restrictive single-use check from the legacy cost model to   │
│ bring its behavior in line with the VPlan model for this     │
│ case.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to      │
│ adjust the legacy cost model in                              │
│ `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getRecurrenceCost` to correctly │
│ cost the scalarization of a first-order recurrence, even     │
│ when it has only one use. We should remove the logic that    │
│ assigns an infinite cost in the single-use case.\n\n[[4211,  │
│ 4217,                                                        │
│ \"llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp\"]]\n\n### │
│ 5. Conclusion\n\nBy removing the pessimistic `if             │
│ (Phi->hasOneUse())` check from the legacy cost model's       │
│ handling of first-order recurrences, we allow it to          │
│ calculate a realistic, finite cost for the operation. This   │
│ makes its costing behavior consistent with the VPlan model   │
│ for this scenario, resolving the disagreement and fixing the │
│ assertion failure. The loop will then be correctly           │
│ vectorized."                                                 │
