│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                  │
│                                                              │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------              │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                               │
│                                                              │
│ The vectorizer is aborting due to an assertion failure in    │
│ `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF`. This assertion is │
│ a consistency check designed to ensure that the new          │
│ VPlan-based cost model and the older, legacy cost model      │
│ agree on the optimal Vectorization Factor (VF).              │
│                                                              │
│ The assertion is:                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ assert((BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||                │
│ BestPlan.hasEarlyExit() ||                                   │
│         planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(Bes │
│ tFactor.Width), ...) ||                                      │
│         planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(Leg │
│ acyVF.Width), ...)) &&                                       │
│        " VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed"); │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ This means the two models have chosen different VFs, and the │
│ discrepancy is not explained by the allowed exceptions       │
│ (early-exit loops or extra VPlan optimizations), pointing to │
│ a fundamental disagreement in how they assess the cost of    │
│ vectorizing this specific loop.                              │
│                                                              │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                 │
│                                                              │
│ The Scalar Evolution analysis provides a crucial clue:       │
│ ```                                                          │
│ %for = phi i32 [ 4, %entry ], [ %iv, %loop ]                 │
│ -->  %for U: [0,9) S: [0,9)  Exits: <<Unknown>>              │
│ LoopDispositions: { %loop: Variant }                         │
│ ```                                                          │
│ SCEV correctly identifies `%for` as "Variant". This is       │
│ because it's a first-order recurrence: its value in the      │
│ current iteration (`%iv`) depends on the induction variable  │
│ from the *previous* iteration. This is different from a      │
│ standard induction or reduction recurrence.                  │
│                                                              │
│ The core of the issue is how the two cost models evaluate    │
│ the profitability of vectorizing this specific type of       │
│ recurrence. The assertion failure implies one model decided  │
│ to vectorize (VF > 1) while the other decided not to (VF =   │
│ 1).                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                   │
│                                                              │
│ The disagreement stems from how the legacy cost model        │
│ handles first-order recurrences. To vectorize the `%for`     │
│ PHI, the vectorizer must "scalarize" the dependency. This    │
│ involves generating code to get the value of `%iv` from the  │
│ last lane of the previous vector iteration and using it as   │
│ the first lane for the `%for` vector in the current          │
│ iteration. This is typically done with `extractelement` and  │
│ `insertelement` instructions, which have a cost.             │
│                                                              │
│ The legacy cost model, specifically in                       │
│ `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getRecurrenceCost`, contains    │
│ logic to estimate the cost of this scalarization. A key part │
│ of this logic is a profitability heuristic:                  │
│                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp           │
│                                                              │
│ // This is a first-order recurrence. This will be            │
│ implemented by vector                                        │
│ // extracting the last scalar value of the VF-1 elements and │
│ then vector                                                  │
│ // inserting the new value to the beginning of the vector.   │
│ if (Phi->hasOneUse()) {                                      │
│   // If the PHI has only one use, we can't scalarize it.     │
│   // TODO: We should be able to scalarize it.                │
│   return Cost->getImpossibleCost();                          │
│ }                                                            │
│ ```                                                          │
│ The code previously had a check that would deem this         │
│ operation too expensive if the recurrence PHI node (`%for`)  │
│ had only one user. In the provided reproducer, `%for` is     │
│ only used by the `sub` instruction, so it has exactly one    │
│ use. Consequently, the legacy cost model assigned a very     │
│ high (effectively infinite) cost, forcing `LegacyVF.Width`   │
│ to be 1 (i.e., do not vectorize).                            │
│                                                              │
│ The newer VPlan-based model, however, correctly estimates a  │
│ finite cost for the necessary shuffle/insert/extract         │
│ operations and determines that vectorization is profitable,  │
│ selecting a `BestFactor.Width` greater than 1.               │
│                                                              │
│ This discrepancy—legacy model refusing to vectorize due to   │
│ the single-use heuristic, and the VPlan model agreeing to—is │
│ the direct cause of the assertion failure. The heuristic in  │
│ the legacy model was overly pessimistic. The fix is to       │
│ remove this overly restrictive single-use check from the     │
│ legacy cost model to bring its behavior in line with the     │
│ VPlan model for this case.                                   │
│                                                              │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to adjust the legacy cost model in                │
│ `LoopVectorizationCostModel::getRecurrenceCost` to correctly │
│ cost the scalarization of a first-order recurrence, even     │
│ when it has only one use. We should remove the logic that    │
│ assigns an infinite cost in the single-use case.             │
│                                                              │
│ [[4211, 4217,                                                │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]]          │
│                                                              │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                            │
│                                                              │
│ By removing the pessimistic `if (Phi->hasOneUse())` check    │
│ from the legacy cost model's handling of first-order         │
│ recurrences, we allow it to calculate a realistic, finite    │
│ cost for the operation. This makes its costing behavior      │
│ consistent with the VPlan model for this scenario, resolving │
│ the disagreement and fixing the assertion failure. The loop  │
│ will then be correctly vectorized.                           │
